{
  "texts": [
    "1. the negative log-likelihood is replaced by a more general notion of risk r(θ), as in PAC-Bayes bounds and in Gibbs posteriors, 2. the minimization over P(Θ) is replaced by the minimization over F, in order to keep things tractable, as in variational inference, 3. finally, the KL divergence is replaced by a general D. Note that this already happened in Theorem 5.3 above.",
    "This triple generalization, and the optimization point of view on Bayesian statistics is strongly advocated in Knoblauch et al. (2022) (in particular reasons to replace KL by D are given in this paper that seem to me more relevant in practice than Theorem 5.3).",
    "In this spirit, Rodríguez-Gálvez et al. (2021) and Chee and Loustau (2021) provided PAC-Bayes type bounds where D is the Wasserstein distance.",
    "Remark 6.1.",
    "When D ̸ = KL, (6.3) is no longer necessarily equivalent to ρ = argmin ρ∈F D (ρ∥π(•|X 1,."
  ]
}